Certainly! Below are the implementations for both C# and JavaScript.

### C# Program

Here's a simple C# console application to calculate the product of 3 and 5 and display the result.

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int number1 = 3;
        int number2 = 5;
        int product = number1 * number2;

        Console.WriteLine("The product of 3 and 5 is: " + product);
    }
}
```

To run this program, you would need to have a C# development environment like Visual Studio or use the .NET Core CLI tools.

### JavaScript Program

Here's how you can calculate the product of 3 and 5 and display the result on a web page using JavaScript and HTML.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Product Calculation</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Product of 3 and 5</h1>
    <p id="result"></p>

    <script>
        const number1 = 3;
        const number2 = 5;
        const product = number1 * number2;

        document.getElementById('result').textContent = 'The product of 3 and 5 is: ' + product;
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

To view this in action, save the HTML code in a `.html` file and open it with a web browser. This will display the calculated product on the page.
